nd the Canonicity of the Mishnah -- t20. The Publication and Early Transmission of the Mishnah -- t21. The Reception of the Mishnah from the Geonic Period to the Age of Print -- t22. The Reception of the Mishnah in the Modern Era -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mishnah is the foundational document of rabbinic Judaism—all of rabbinic law, from ancient to modern times, is based on the Talmud, and the Talmud, in turn, is based on the Mishnah. But the Mishnah is also an elusive document; its sources and setting are obscure, as are its genre and purpose.In January 2021 the Harvard Center for Jewish Studies and the Julis-Rabinowitz Program on Jewish and Israeli Law of the Harvard Law School co-sponsored a conference devoted to the simple yet complicated question: “What is the Mishnah?” Leading scholars from the United States, Europe, and Israel assessed the state of the art in Mishnah studies; and the papers delivered at that conference form the basis of this collection. Learned yet accessible, What Is the Mishnah? gives readers a clear sense of current and future direction of Mishnah studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aBerkowitz, Beth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Shaye J. D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCohn, Naftali S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Shamma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Uziel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurstenberg, Yair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGafni, Chanan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l